.</p>
<p>

Eyring was also a leader in <denomination wordnetid="108146782" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../935/5935.xml">
The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints</link></denomination>
.  He served as the first president of the New England Mission from 1937-1939.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>  While President of the New England mission Eyring exerted efforts to keep Latter-day Saint students at <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/18426501.xml">
Harvard University</link></university>
, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../061/19061.xml">
MIT</link> and other Boston area institutions of higher learning active in the church.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref></p>
<p>

Eyring was the uncle of the noted physicist <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../916/176916.xml">
Henry Eyring</link></scientist>
</person>
.  Carl Eyring was married to Fern Chipman.  She was the sister of Lorena Chipman, who was the wife of <scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../937/179937.xml">
Harvey Fletcher</link></scientist>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref>  </p>
<p>

From 1924 until 1951, except for his time as missiom president, Eyring served as the dean of the college of Arts and Sciences at <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../058/82058.xml">
Brigham Young University</link></university>
.</p>
